[
  {
    "text": "If someone called you scum,",
    "start": 7.618,
    "duration": 2.129
  },
  {
    "text": "you'd probably be offended,",
    "start": 9.747,
    "duration": 1.704
  },
  {
    "text": "but scientifically,",
    "start": 11.451,
    "duration": 1.417
  },
  {
    "text": "they might not be far off.",
    "start": 12.868,
    "duration": 1.583
  },
  {
    "text": "Have you ever thought about",
    "start": 14.451,
    "duration": 1.052
  },
  {
    "text": "where your food comes from?",
    "start": 15.503,
    "duration": 1.864
  },
  {
    "text": "You might say it comes from",
    "start": 17.367,
    "duration": 1.354
  },
  {
    "text": "plants, animals, or even fungi,",
    "start": 18.721,
    "duration": 1.683
  },
  {
    "text": "but you'd probably rather not",
    "start": 20.404,
    "duration": 1.556
  },
  {
    "text": "think about the rotting organisms and poop",
    "start": 21.96,
    "duration": 1.76
  },
  {
    "text": "that feed those plants, animals, and fungi.",
    "start": 23.72,
    "duration": 3.147
  },
  {
    "text": "So really, you and most of the matter in your body",
    "start": 26.867,
    "duration": 2.485
  },
  {
    "text": "are just two or three degrees of separation",
    "start": 29.352,
    "duration": 2.583
  },
  {
    "text": "from things like pond scum.",
    "start": 31.935,
    "duration": 2.837
  },
  {
    "text": "All species in an ecosystem,",
    "start": 34.772,
    "duration": 1.792
  },
  {
    "text": "from the creatures in a coral reef",
    "start": 36.564,
    "duration": 1.545
  },
  {
    "text": "to the fish in a lake",
    "start": 38.109,
    "duration": 1.376
  },
  {
    "text": "to the lions on the savannah,",
    "start": 39.485,
    "duration": 1.336
  },
  {
    "text": "are directly or indirectly",
    "start": 40.821,
    "duration": 1.541
  },
  {
    "text": "nourished by dead stuff.",
    "start": 42.362,
    "duration": 1.963
  },
  {
    "text": "Most of the organic matter in our bodies,",
    "start": 44.325,
    "duration": 2.501
  },
  {
    "text": "if we trace it back far enough,",
    "start": 46.826,
    "duration": 1.791
  },
  {
    "text": "comes from CO2 and water",
    "start": 48.617,
    "duration": 1.796
  },
  {
    "text": "through photosynthesis.",
    "start": 50.413,
    "duration": 1.836
  },
  {
    "text": "Plants use the energy from sunlight",
    "start": 52.249,
    "duration": 1.821
  },
  {
    "text": "to transform carbon dioxide and water from the environment",
    "start": 54.07,
    "duration": 3.108
  },
  {
    "text": "into glucose and oxygen.",
    "start": 57.178,
    "duration": 2.409
  },
  {
    "text": "That glucose is then transformed",
    "start": 59.587,
    "duration": 1.696
  },
  {
    "text": "into more complex organic molecules",
    "start": 61.283,
    "duration": 1.418
  },
  {
    "text": "to form leaves, stems, roots, fruit, and so on.",
    "start": 62.701,
    "duration": 4.144
  },
  {
    "text": "The energy stored in these organic molecules",
    "start": 66.845,
    "duration": 1.919
  },
  {
    "text": "supports the food chains with which we're familiar.",
    "start": 68.764,
    "duration": 2.793
  },
  {
    "text": "You've probably seen illustrations like this",
    "start": 71.557,
    "duration": 2.393
  },
  {
    "text": "or this.",
    "start": 73.95,
    "duration": 1.587
  },
  {
    "text": "These green food chains",
    "start": 75.537,
    "duration": 1.444
  },
  {
    "text": "start with living plants at their base.",
    "start": 76.981,
    "duration": 2.26
  },
  {
    "text": "But in real-life terrestrial ecosystems,",
    "start": 79.241,
    "duration": 2.793
  },
  {
    "text": "less than 10% of plant matter",
    "start": 82.034,
    "duration": 1.955
  },
  {
    "text": "is eaten while it's still alive.",
    "start": 83.989,
    "duration": 2.013
  },
  {
    "text": "What about the other 90?",
    "start": 86.002,
    "duration": 1.699
  },
  {
    "text": "Well, just look at the ground",
    "start": 87.701,
    "duration": 1.458
  },
  {
    "text": "on an autumn day.",
    "start": 89.159,
    "duration": 1.167
  },
  {
    "text": "Living plants shed dead body parts:",
    "start": 90.326,
    "duration": 1.753
  },
  {
    "text": "fallen leaves, broken branches,",
    "start": 92.079,
    "duration": 1.669
  },
  {
    "text": "and even underground roots.",
    "start": 93.748,
    "duration": 1.753
  },
  {
    "text": "Many plants are lucky enough",
    "start": 95.501,
    "duration": 1.418
  },
  {
    "text": "to go their whole lives without being eaten,",
    "start": 96.919,
    "duration": 1.698
  },
  {
    "text": "eventually dying and leaving remains.",
    "start": 98.617,
    "duration": 2.637
  },
  {
    "text": "All of these uneaten, undigested, and dead plant parts,",
    "start": 101.254,
    "duration": 3.286
  },
  {
    "text": "that 90% of terrestrial plant matter?",
    "start": 104.54,
    "duration": 2.66
  },
  {
    "text": "That becomes detritus,",
    "start": 107.2,
    "duration": 1.646
  },
  {
    "text": "the base of what we call the brown food chain,",
    "start": 108.846,
    "duration": 2.854
  },
  {
    "text": "which looks more like this.",
    "start": 111.7,
    "duration": 2.334
  },
  {
    "text": "What happens to plants",
    "start": 114.034,
    "duration": 1.441
  },
  {
    "text": "also happens to all other organisms up the food chain:",
    "start": 115.475,
    "duration": 2.589
  },
  {
    "text": "some are eaten alive,",
    "start": 118.064,
    "duration": 1.334
  },
  {
    "text": "but most are eaten only",
    "start": 119.398,
    "duration": 1.42
  },
  {
    "text": "when they're dead and rotting.",
    "start": 120.818,
    "duration": 1.791
  },
  {
    "text": "And all along this food chain,",
    "start": 122.609,
    "duration": 1.533
  },
  {
    "text": "living things shed organic matter",
    "start": 124.142,
    "duration": 1.889
  },
  {
    "text": "and expel digestive waste",
    "start": 126.031,
    "duration": 1.624
  },
  {
    "text": "before dying and leaving their remains to decay.",
    "start": 127.655,
    "duration": 3.045
  },
  {
    "text": "All that death sounds grim, right?",
    "start": 130.7,
    "duration": 2.546
  },
  {
    "text": "But it's not.",
    "start": 133.246,
    "duration": 1.335
  },
  {
    "text": "All detritus is ultimately consumed",
    "start": 134.581,
    "duration": 2.003
  },
  {
    "text": "by microbes and other scavengers,",
    "start": 136.584,
    "duration": 1.949
  },
  {
    "text": "so it actually forms the base of the brown food chain",
    "start": 138.533,
    "duration": 2.636
  },
  {
    "text": "that supports many other organisms,",
    "start": 141.169,
    "duration": 2.283
  },
  {
    "text": "including us.",
    "start": 143.452,
    "duration": 1.916
  },
  {
    "text": "Scientists are learning",
    "start": 145.368,
    "duration": 1.333
  },
  {
    "text": "that this detritus",
    "start": 146.701,
    "duration": 0.768
  },
  {
    "text": "is an unexpectedly huge energy source,",
    "start": 147.469,
    "duration": 2.243
  },
  {
    "text": "fueling most natural ecosystems.",
    "start": 149.712,
    "duration": 2.173
  },
  {
    "text": "But the interactions within an ecosystem",
    "start": 151.885,
    "duration": 2.297
  },
  {
    "text": "are even more complex than that.",
    "start": 154.182,
    "duration": 2.294
  },
  {
    "text": "What a food chain really represents",
    "start": 156.476,
    "duration": 1.642
  },
  {
    "text": "is a single pathway of energy flow.",
    "start": 158.118,
    "duration": 2.533
  },
  {
    "text": "And within any ecosystem,",
    "start": 160.651,
    "duration": 2.043
  },
  {
    "text": "many of these flows",
    "start": 162.694,
    "duration": 1.165
  },
  {
    "text": "are linked together",
    "start": 163.859,
    "duration": 1.128
  },
  {
    "text": "to form a rich network of interactions,",
    "start": 164.987,
    "duration": 1.376
  },
  {
    "text": "or food web,",
    "start": 166.363,
    "duration": 2.376
  },
  {
    "text": "with dead matter supporting that network at every step.",
    "start": 168.739,
    "duration": 3.504
  },
  {
    "text": "The resulting food web",
    "start": 172.243,
    "duration": 1.295
  },
  {
    "text": "is so connected",
    "start": 173.538,
    "duration": 1.079
  },
  {
    "text": "that almost every species",
    "start": 174.617,
    "duration": 1.212
  },
  {
    "text": "is no more than two degrees from detritus,",
    "start": 175.829,
    "duration": 2.203
  },
  {
    "text": "even us humans.",
    "start": 178.032,
    "duration": 1.97
  },
  {
    "text": "You probably don't eat rotting things,",
    "start": 180.002,
    "duration": 1.614
  },
  {
    "text": "poop, or pond scum directly,",
    "start": 181.616,
    "duration": 2.167
  },
  {
    "text": "but your food sources probably do.",
    "start": 183.783,
    "duration": 2.308
  },
  {
    "text": "Many animals we eat",
    "start": 186.091,
    "duration": 1.75
  },
  {
    "text": "either feed directly on detritus themselves,",
    "start": 187.841,
    "duration": 2.086
  },
  {
    "text": "like pork, poultry, mushrooms, shellfish,",
    "start": 189.927,
    "duration": 1.924
  },
  {
    "text": "or catfish and other bottom feeders,",
    "start": 191.851,
    "duration": 3.624
  },
  {
    "text": "or they are fed animal by-products.",
    "start": 195.475,
    "duration": 1.416
  },
  {
    "text": "So, if you're thinking nature is full of waste,",
    "start": 196.891,
    "duration": 2.795
  },
  {
    "text": "you're right.",
    "start": 199.686,
    "duration": 1.259
  },
  {
    "text": "But one organism's garbage is another's gold,",
    "start": 200.945,
    "duration": 2.621
  },
  {
    "text": "and all that rotting dead stuff",
    "start": 203.566,
    "duration": 1.459
  },
  {
    "text": "ultimately provides the energy that nourishes us",
    "start": 205.025,
    "duration": 2.127
  },
  {
    "text": "and most of life on Earth,",
    "start": 207.152,
    "duration": 1.918
  },
  {
    "text": "as it passes through the food web.",
    "start": 209.07,
    "duration": 1.922
  },
  {
    "text": "Now that's some food for thought.",
    "start": 210.992,
    "duration": 4.183
  }
]